## Command Pattern (For Undo/Redo or Input)

```
using System;

/// <summary>
/// Command interface for undoable actions.
/// </summary>
public interface ICommand
{
    void Execute();
    void Undo();
}

/// <summary>
/// Command manager for executing and undoing commands.
/// </summary>
public class CommandManager
{
    private System.Collections.Generic.Stack<ICommand> _undoStack = new System.Collections.Generic.Stack<ICommand>();
    private System.Collections.Generic.Stack<ICommand> _redoStack = new System.Collections.Generic.Stack<ICommand>();

    public void ExecuteCommand(ICommand command)
    {
        command.Execute();
        _undoStack.Push(command);
        _redoStack.Clear(); // Clear redo stack when new command is executed
    }

    public void Undo()
    {
        if (_undoStack.Count > 0)
        {
            ICommand command = _undoStack.Pop();
            command.Undo();
            _redoStack.Push(command);
        }
    }

    public void Redo()
    {
        if (_redoStack.Count > 0)
        {
            ICommand command = _redoStack.Pop();
            command.Execute();
            _undoStack.Push(command);
        }
    }
}
```

## Best Practices

### Separation of Concerns
- **Core**: Base systems, managers, utilities
- **Gameplay**: Game-specific logic, mechanics
- **UI**: UI controllers and views (UI Toolkit)
- **Data**: ScriptableObjects, data structures

### Dependency Direction
- Core → Gameplay → UI
- Never let Core depend on Gameplay or UI
- Use interfaces for cross-layer communication

### Assembly Definitions
- Create separate `.asmdef` files for each major system
- Reference only what you need
- Keep Core assembly dependency-free

### ScriptableObject Usage
- Configuration data (weapons, enemies, items)
- Event channels for decoupling
- Runtime variables for shared state
- Sets for collections (e.g., all enemies, all items)
